          "body": "The chapter closes with David turning from Solomon to all the leaders of Israel (22:17–19). The private charge becomes a national commission. David's rhetoric to the leaders mirrors his charge to Solomon in miniature: divine indicative ('is not the LORD your God with you? Has He not given you rest?' — 22:18) followed by human imperative ('now set your heart and your soul to seek the LORD your God; arise, therefore, and build' — 22:19). The indicative precedes and grounds the imperative: what God has already done (given rest, subdued the land) is the platform for what the leaders must now do. The final verse (22:19) is the chapter's most comprehensive command, and its sequence is telling: first 'seek the LORD' (interior disposition), then 'arise and build' (external action), and the goal is bringing the ark of the covenant and the holy vessels 'into the house that is to be built for the name of the LORD.' The ark — the locus of God's covenant presence — is the reason for the building. The Temple is not an end in itself; it is the permanent housing for the covenant relationship. For the Chronicler's post-exilic audience, who had experienced the ark's absence and the Temple's destruction, this closing vision is not merely historical — it is eschatological hope expressed in construction terms."
